@endnode

@node Configuration "Configuration"
@{b}Configuration@{ub}

@{fg shine}ptable.library@{fg text} has no preferences file of its own. Its behaviour is
configured from two places.

@{b}1. On-disk RDB metadata (cold-boot path).@{ub} Each RDB partition carries its
own boot priority and flags, and the library uses them as-is:

  @{b}RDB partition flag@{ub}  @{b}BootPri@{ub}  @{b}Result@{ub}                    
  ------------------  -------  ------------------------  
  normal              >= 0     bootable: appears in the  
                               Early Startup boot list   
  normal              < 0      non-bootable: mounted as  
                               a DOS volume              
  NOMOUNT (bit 1)     any      published but never       
                               mounted (skipped)         

To change which partition boots, or whether one mounts, you edit the RDB
with a partitioning tool (e.g. HDToolBox), not the library.

@{b}2. The consumer's mount configuration ( @{fg shine}MountCfg@{fg text} , DOS-time path).@{ub}
@{fg shine}MountPartitions@{fg text} takes an optional @{fg shine}MountCfg@{fg text} that supplies a global mount
@{fg shine}Flags@{fg text} value, a global @{fg shine}CONTROL@{fg text} string, and a per-filesystem override
table. The library resolves each partition's @{fg shine}Flags@{fg text} and @{fg shine}CONTROL@{fg text} by its
DosType (matching the high three bytes, e.g. @{fg shine}FAT\0@{fg text} ), falling back to
the global value. Passing @{fg shine}0@{fg text} selects cold-boot defaults.

For @{fg shine}compactflash.device@{fg text} , these values come from @{fg shine}ENV:cfd.prefs@{fg text} : the
@{fg shine}FLAGS@{fg text} and @{fg shine}CONTROL@{fg text} keys, both global and @{fg shine}_<fs>@{fg text} per filesystem (e.g.
@{fg shine}FLAGS_FAT@{fg text} , @{fg shine}CONTROL_FAT@{fg text} ). So to change how hotplugged cards mount, you
edit @{fg shine}cfd.prefs@{fg text} , not @{fg shine}ptable.library@{fg text} . The resolved values are recorded
per partition and shown live by @{fg shine}lsptres@{fg text} in its @{fg shine}MFlg@{fg text} and @{fg shine}Ctrl@{fg text} columns.
This is only the automount path: a partition mounted statically instead
shows the Flags and CONTROL its own handler opened the device with (see @{"Partition naming" link partition_naming}
), since that handler records them the same way via @{fg shine}RegisterPartition@{fg text} .

The full user-facing reference for the @{fg shine}cfd.prefs@{fg text} keys ( @{fg shine}AUTOMOUNT@{fg text} ,
@{fg shine}FLAGS@{fg text} , @{fg shine}CONTROL@{fg text} , @{fg shine}UNMOUNT@{fg text} , and the per-filesystem overrides), plus
deployment defaults and the removable-media model, is
@{fg shine}compactflash.device@{fg text} 's automount guide ( @{fg shine}automount.guide@{fg text} ).

@{b}Detach policy (card removal).@{ub} The library offers two ways to handle a
removed card's partitions, and the consumer chooses per filesystem:

  * @{b}Unmount and remove ( @{fg shine}compactflash.device@{fg text} default), @{fg shine}UnmountPartitions@{fg text} with a
    prefix list:@{ub} stop the handler, remove its DOS node (ACTION_DIE + RemDosEntry +
    free the node), and drop the partition's resource entry from the list.
    @{fg shine}compactflash.device@{fg text} applies this to all supported filesystems by default; an
    explicit @{fg shine}UNMOUNT@{fg text} key in @{fg shine}cfd.prefs@{fg text} restricts it to the listed ones, e.g.
    @{fg shine}UNMOUNT FAT@{fg text} . With no prefix list, @{fg shine}UnmountPartitions@{fg text} unmounts and frees every
    partition for the device and unit.
  * @{b}Keep, @{fg shine}MarkAbsent@{fg text} :@{ub} clear @{fg shine}PRESENT@{fg text} but keep the DOS node and handler in memory.
    The entry stays listed as absent-but-mounted ( @{fg shine}---M@{fg text} ), and reinserting the
    same card reattaches it without re-initialising the handler. This is the
    native AmigaOS removable-media model. For @{fg shine}compactflash.device@{fg text} this applies to
    filesystems not listed in an explicit @{fg shine}UNMOUNT@{fg text} key ( @{fg shine}UNMOUNT NONE@{fg text} keeps
    everything).

----------------------------------------
@{"<< Prev" link Flows}  @{"Contents" link Main}  @{"Next >>" link Partition_naming}

@endnode

@node Partition_naming "Partition naming"
@{b}Partition naming@{ub}

@{b}RDB@{ub} partitions keep their on-disk name ( @{fg shine}pb_DriveName@{fg text} ) verbatim (e.g.
@{fg shine}DH0@{fg text} ).

@{b}MBR, GPT, and flat@{ub} partitions carry no on-disk name, so the library
synthesizes one: @{fg shine}PREFIX@{fg text} + unit-letter + partition-number.

  * @{b}PREFIX:@{ub} a short device abbreviation from a built-in table, or, for devices not
    in the table, the device's base name with @{fg shine}.device@{fg text} stripped and the @{fg shine}A-Z@{fg text} and @{fg shine}0-9@{fg text}
    characters uppercased. Currently only @{fg shine}compactflash.device@{fg text} has an abbreviation
    ( @{fg shine}CF@{fg text} ); everything else falls back to the base name.
  * @{b}unit-letter:@{ub} lowercase @{fg shine}a@{fg text} + unit (@{fg shine}a@{fg text} = unit 0, @{fg shine}b@{fg text} = unit 1, up to @{fg shine}p@{fg text} = unit 15).
  * @{b}partition-number:@{ub} 0-based decimal.

  @{b}Device@{ub}                     @{b}Unit@{ub}  @{b}Synthesized names@{ub}  
  -------------------------  ----  -----------------  
  @{fg shine}compactflash.device@{fg text}        0     @{fg shine}CFa0@{fg text}, @{fg shine}CFa1@{fg text}, @{fg shine}CFa2@{fg text}   
  (abbrev @{fg shine}CF@{fg text} )                                        
  @{fg shine}scsi.device@{fg text} (base name to  0     @{fg shine}SCSIa0@{fg text}, @{fg shine}SCSIa1@{fg text}     
  @{fg shine}SCSI@{fg text} )                                              
  @{fg shine}scsi.device@{fg text}                2     @{fg shine}SCSIc0@{fg text}, @{fg shine}SCSIc1@{fg text}     
  @{fg shine}mfm.device@{fg text} (base name to   1     @{fg shine}MFMb0@{fg text}, @{fg shine}MFMb1@{fg text}       
  @{fg shine}MFM@{fg text} )                                               

To give a device its own abbreviation instead of the base-name fallback,
add it to @{fg shine}s_devAbbrevTable@{fg text} in @{fg shine}../src/ptable_scan.s@{fg text}
(../src/ptable_scan.s). Name clashes with existing mounts are uniquified
at register time.

@{b}Overriding the name with a static mountlist.@{ub} The synthesized name is
only the @{i}scan@{ui} name. If you mount a partition yourself with a static
@{fg shine}DEVS:DOSDrivers@{fg text} entry, the handler registers the real DOS device name
(along with the Flags and CONTROL it opened the device with) back onto
the published entry, matched by device, unit, and start block, so the
partition is reachable under the name you chose and @{fg shine}lsptres@{fg text} shows that
mount's @{fg shine}MFlg@{fg text} and @{fg shine}Ctrl@{fg text} . @{fg shine}lsptres@{fg text} then shows both names, as
@{fg shine}scanname>dosname@{fg text} : e.g. @{fg shine}CFa0>MS0@{fg text} is the partition the library scanned as
@{fg shine}CFa0@{fg text} , mounted as @{fg shine}MS0:@{fg text} from your mountlist. This is the same
@{fg shine}RegisterPartition@{fg text} path cfd's automount uses, so the @{fg shine}MFlg@{fg text} and @{fg shine}Ctrl@{fg text}
columns are accurate whether a partition was automounted or mounted
statically. RDB partitions always keep their on-disk name.

----------------------------------------
@{"<< Prev" link Configuration}  @{"Contents" link Main}  @{"Next >>" link What_it_looks_like__serial_debug_}

@endnode

@node What_it_looks_like__serial_debug_ "What it looks like (serial debug)"
@{b}What it looks like (serial debug)@{ub}

The @{fg shine}full@{fg text} build prints its progress to the serial port at 9600 baud. The
library tags its own lines @{fg shine}[PT]@{fg text} , and the cold-boot module
@{fg shine}compactflash.dosboot@{fg text} tags the cold-boot hand-off @{fg shine}[CFD] boot:@{fg text} . The @{fg shine}small@{fg text}
build is silent.

@{b}Cold boot, RDB autoboot.@{ub} @{fg shine}compactflash.dosboot@{fg text} opens the library and
calls @{fg shine}BootScanPartitions@{fg text} ; the library walks the RDB and registers the
mountable partitions:

@{fg highlight}
  [CFD] boot: open ptable.library ...
  [CFD] boot: ptable.library not preloaded, InitResident()...
  [CFD] boot: BootScanPartitions(compactflash.device,0)
  [PT] cold boot: scanning for partitions
  [PT] RDB partition table
  [PT] partitions found: 5
  [PT] - skip  SDH10 (no-mount)
  [PT] - skip  SDH11 (no-mount)
  [PT] + boot  SDH0 (PFS, 512 MB)
  [PT] + mount SDH1 (PFS, 4096 MB)
  [PT] + mount SDH2 (PFS, 21767 MB)
  [PT] cold boot done, partitions registered: 3
@{fg text}

Five partitions are found; the two NOMOUNT entries are skipped, one
bootable is registered ( @{fg shine}+ boot@{fg text} ) and two mountable ( @{fg shine}+ mount@{fg text} ), so
three are registered.

@{b}Hotplug, DOS-time scan.@{ub} An inserted card is scanned, its partitions
published, then mounted by the consumer's mount worker. Here a GPT card
with three FAT partitions in the PCMCIA slot, automounted:

@{fg highlight}
  [PT] scanning for partitions
  [PT] GPT partition table
  [PT] partitions found: 3
  [PT] mounting partitions
  [PT] mounted CFa0 (FAT, 2048 MB)
  [PT] mounted CFa1 (FAT, 4096 MB)
  [PT] mounted CFa2 (FAT, 8192 MB)
@{fg text}

The resulting @{fg shine}partition.resource@{fg text} , listed by @{fg shine}lsptres@{fg text} (columns explained
in @{"  __PAIRED_2__  " link "lsptres.guide/Main"} ; @{fg shine}Text@{fg text} is the four-character text of the DosType):

@{fg highlight}
  Name         Device        Unit Part Src Pri DosType    Text Flags MFlg Ctrl
  ------------ ------------- ---- ---- --- --- ---------- ---- ----- ----- ----------
  CFa0         compactflash.    0    0 GPT   0 0x46415400 FAT. P--M      0 -d-D
  CFa1         compactflash.    0    1 GPT   0 0x46415400 FAT. P--M      0 -d-D
  CFa2         compactflash.    0    2 GPT   0 0x46415400 FAT. P--M      0 -d-D
@{fg text}

The three FAT partitions show the synthesized scan name ( @{fg shine}CFa0@{fg text} .. @{fg shine}CFa2@{fg text}
), all mounted ( @{fg shine}P--M@{fg text} ), with the @{fg shine}Ctrl@{fg text} value @{fg shine}-d-D@{fg text} resolved from
@{fg shine}CONTROL_FAT@{fg text} in @{fg shine}cfd.prefs@{fg text} .

@{b}Hotplug, card removed.@{ub} On removal the library has two policies (see @{"Detach policy" link configuration} ).
With the keep policy ( @{fg shine}UNMOUNT NONE@{fg text} in @{fg shine}cfd.prefs@{fg text} , or a filesystem not
listed in an explicit @{fg shine}UNMOUNT@{fg text} key) each partition's handler stays in
memory and is just marked absent, so the entry stays in the resource
with @{fg shine}PRESENT@{fg text} cleared ( @{fg shine}---M@{fg text} ) and reinserting the same card reattaches
it:

@{fg highlight}
  [PT] card removed, media absent
@{fg text}

@{fg highlight}
  Name         Device        Unit Part Src Pri DosType    Text Flags MFlg Ctrl
  ------------ ------------- ---- ---- --- --- ---------- ---- ----- ----- ----------
  CFa0         compactflash.    0    0 GPT   0 0x46415400 FAT. ---M      0 -d-D
  CFa1         compactflash.    0    1 GPT   0 0x46415400 FAT. ---M      0 -d-D
  CFa2         compactflash.    0    2 GPT   0 0x46415400 FAT. ---M      0 -d-D
@{fg text}

By @{fg shine}compactflash.device@{fg text} 's default (all supported filesystems in the
unmount list, here equally with @{fg shine}UNMOUNT FAT@{fg text} ), the FAT partitions are
instead unmounted and removed entirely: handlers stopped, DOS nodes
removed, and dropped from the resource (the list ends up empty):

@{fg highlight}
  [PT] card removed, media absent
  [PT] unmounting partitions
  [PT] unmounted CFa0
  [PT] unmounted CFa1
  [PT] unmounted CFa2
@{fg text}

----------------------------------------
